template.title: RDA DCS 1.1
template.description: This template will be used to improve support for the interchange format RDA DMP Common Standard.

sections.title: Cost
sections.comment: List costs related to data management. Providing multiple instances of a 'Cost' allows to break down costs into details. Providing one 'Cost' instance allows to provide one aggregated sum.

sections.title: Host
sections.comment: Provide information on quality of service provided by infrastructure (e.g. repository) where data is stored

sections.title: Contributor
sections.comment: List people that play any role in data management related to this DMP, e.g. responsible for performing actions described in this DMP.

sections.title: Dataset
sections.comment: Describe data on a non-technical level.

sections.title: License
sections.comment: List all licenses applied to a specific distribution of data.

sections.title: Project
sections.comment: Any projects related to a DMP, regarding funding and grants.

sections.title: Distribution
sections.comment: Provide technical information on a specific instance of data.

questions.question: DMP id
questions.help_text: Identifier for the DMP itself

questions.question: Description
questions.help_text: To provide any free-form text information on a DMP

questions.question: Language
questions.help_text: Language of the DMP expressed using ISO 639-3

questions.question: Ethical issues exist
questions.help_text: Are there any ethical issues related to data that this DMP describes?

questions.question: Ethical issues description
questions.help_text: Describe any ethical issues related to data in this DMP or any dataset in this DMP

questions.question: Ethical issues report url
questions.help_text: Where can a protocol from a meeting with an ethical commitee be found?

questions.question: Title
questions.help_text: Title is a property in both Dataset and Distribution, in compliance with W3C DCAT. In some cases these might be identical, but in most cases the Dataset represents a more abstract concept, while the distribution can point to a specific file.

questions.question: Description
questions.help_text: Description is a property in both Dataset and Distribution, in compliance with W3C DCAT. In some cases these might be identical, but in most cases the Dataset represents a more abstract concept, while the distribution can point to a specific file.

questions.question: Language
questions.help_text: Language of the dataset expressed using ISO 639-3

questions.question: Type
questions.help_text: If appropriate, type according to: DataCite and/or COAR dictionary. Otherwise use the common name for the type, e.g. raw data, software, survey, etc. https://schema.datacite.org/meta/kernel-4.1/doc/DataCite-MetadataKernel_v4.1.pdf http://vocabularies.coar-repositories.org/pubby/resource_type.html

questions.question: Contact id
questions.help_text: Identifier for a contact person

questions.question: Name
questions.help_text: Name of the contact person

questions.question: Are there other contributors besides the contact?
questions.help_text: This is optional. You may add more than one.

questions.question: Do you at this time have information about at least one project that will be/is using this DMP?
questions.help_text: This is optional, and you can add more than one. Select "No" to skip.

questions.question: Title
questions.help_text: Project title

questions.question: Description
questions.help_text: Project description, optional.

questions.question: Start
questions.help_text: Project start date, if known. Optional. Encoded using the relevant ISO 8601 Date and Time compliant string.

questions.question: End
questions.help_text: Project end date, if known. Optional. Encoded using the relevant ISO 8601 Date and Time compliant string.

questions.question: Is there any plans or info about funding for this project?
questions.help_text: This is optional, and you can add more than one. Select "no" to skip.

questions.question: Does the dataset have a distribution?
questions.help_text: Select "yes" to add information about the distribution, you can have more than one. A distribution of a dataset may have one or more licenses, and may be hosted at one or more locations, aka. "hosts".

questions.question: Title
questions.help_text: Title is a property in both Dataset and Distribution, in compliance with W3C DCAT. In some cases these might be identical, but in most cases the Dataset represents a more abstract concept, while the distribution can point to a specific file.

questions.question: Description
questions.help_text: Description is a property in both Dataset and Distribution, in compliance with W3C DCAT. In some cases these might be identical, but in most cases the Dataset represents a more abstract concept, while the distribution can point to a specific file.

questions.question: Format
questions.help_text: Format according to: https://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml if appropriate, otherwise use the common name for this format

questions.question: Access url
questions.help_text: A URL of the resource that gives access to a distribution of the dataset. e.g. landing page.

questions.question: Download url
questions.help_text: The URL of the downloadable file in a given format. E.g. CSV file or RDF file.

questions.question: Data access
questions.help_text: Indicates access mode for data.

questions.question: Available until
questions.help_text: Indicates how long this distribution will be/ should be available. Encoded using the relevant ISO 8601 Date and Time compliant string

questions.question: Do you at this time know anything about where the distribution will be stored?
questions.help_text: Select "yes" to add more info about things like backups, versioning, geographical location, internet location (URL) or repository certification. You can add more than one, redundancy is a good idea.

questions.question: Storage type
questions.help_text: The type of storage required

questions.question: URL
questions.help_text: The URL of the system hosting a distribution of a dataset

questions.question: Geo location
questions.help_text: Country code from ISO 3166-1

questions.question: Does this distribution have a license?
questions.help_text: Select "yes" to tag the distribution with a license, you can have more than one.This is vital for re-use.

questions.question: License
questions.help_text: A link to a license. This link should be publicly accessible.

questions.question: Start date
questions.help_text:
From when is the distribution available with this license? If the date is set in the future, it indicates an embargo period.

Encoded using the relevant ISO 8601 Date and Time compliant string

questions.question: Do you know of any costs regarding the data management?
questions.help_text: This is optional. Select "yes" in order to list costs related to data management. You can have more than one, allowing  a breakdown of detailed costs, or answer only once in order to provide a single aggregated sum.

questions.question: Title
questions.help_text: Some title to refer to the cost, for instance "storage and backup", "upload costs", "AWS", "co-lo"...

questions.question: Description
questions.help_text: More in-depth description of the cost. Optional.

questions.question: Currency code
questions.help_text: Three-letter currency code as defined in ISO 4217. If the currency is not covered by ISO 4217, please notify ISO.

questions.question: Value
questions.help_text: The actual cost, as an integer, if you know it at this time. Please also fill in the currency code if you know the value.
